<br>
In fact, during a debate with Gore (the second or third one), both candidates were asked which instances of recent intervention by the US in world affairs they would have supported.<br>
<br>
I remember very vividly that Bush didnt even recognize one of them and stumbled in his answer. The ones he did recall, for the most part, he said he opposed... and he attacked Clinton for &quot;policing the world,&quot; even though Clinton used restrained force and superior firepower during the conflict in the Balkaans to force stability in the region.<br>
<br>
=============================================<br>
<br>
Those who say 9/11 changed everything have no understanding of history. 9/11 didnt change anything--it merely underscored lessons that should have been learned long ago, that were forgotten.<br>
<br>
The US is very much a part of the world community, whether it wants to be or not. I hope I live to see the day we realize this and start participating as a member of that community and not as an arrogant god that demands compliance with its standards and beliefs, but then refuses to answer to the inquiries of others.<br>
<br>
=============================================<br>
<br>
There are so many instances where the notion of &quot;peace through superior firepower&quot; can be shown to be false that making that statement and leaving it that simple made me blink.<br>
<br>
Look at the Middle East. Israel has one of the most advanced military machines in the world, and has the US constantly on its side. No greater firepower has been assembled in the history of the world. The Palestinians have virtually nothing. Result? No peace, nor will there be. Not due to &quot;military might.&quot;<br>
<br>
Look at 9/11. Our firepower certainly didnt help us much there, hmm? We sure smacked the Taliban around though. <br>
<br>
Look at Vietnam. My dad's a Marine, and was wounded fighting over there. At one point his unit, while entrenched, got attacked by a bunch of North Vietnamese irregulars wielding .22s and farm tools. Many of them in their mid-teens. His unit had to mow them down... Yet the North Vietnamese succeeded in their objectives, despite US &quot;firepower.&quot;<br>
<br>
There are instances where superior firepower and the threat of its use prevent conflict, I agree. The conflict in the Balkaan a few years ago is a good example, as is the standoff between China and Taiwan.<br>
<br>
But there are also a myriad of instances where it does not, because when determined, commited, absolute willpower and resistance meets superior firepower, firepower will lose more often than not in the long run, unless you are willing to commit genocide.<br>
<br>
=============================================<br>
<br>
Edward, you stated earlier that 9/11 was not the result of someone hating the US, but of someone thinking that the US was weak--that they could attack the US and get away with it.<br>
<br>
You're forgetting that those most of those who attacked the US didnt &quot;get away with it.&quot; They died piloting the planes.   Same with the Palestinian bombers. They dont care about &quot;weak&quot; or &quot;strong.&quot; They were willing to sacrifice their lives because of their beliefs. &quot;Firepower&quot; doesnt figure into beliefs of that intensity. <br>
<br>
Bin Ladin is many things, but unintelligent is not one of them. He knew he might die as a result of his actions. So did those around him. Im sure that, even given the US responce, they would do what they did again in an instance.<br>
<br>
You listed a number of attacks previous to 9/11 that were not responded to by the US as being a reason that 9/11 occurred. By that rationale, the fact that we beat the tar out of the Taliban will mean that such attacks will stop, right? Because the world has seen how mighty we are. <br>
<br>
I hope that is the case, but doubt it very much.<br>
<br>
=============================================<br>
<br>
One last point... Edward, you stated that following 9/11 the US could have launched a few ICBMs, taken out tens of millions of people, and the rest of the world would have &quot;supported us.&quot;<br>
<br>
I believe that statement is STUNNINGLY inaccurate. Amazingly so.<br>
<br>
As much as I respect your knowledge of history and the complex nature of international relations, I would say that statement is an example of what I have said all along--that you, and many other Americans, have such an intensely one-sided view of world affairs its easy, if not inevitable, to become blind to the existence and opinions of those outside the US.<br>
<br>
I believe that, had we used ICBMs to take out tens of millions of innocent people in responce to 9/11, the world reaction would have been immediate, intense, and increadibly scathing.<br>
<br>
Fortunately, that will remain a matter of speculation on my part, since we didnt.<br>
<br>
This time anyway. I hope we never find out for real.<br>
