<br>
The example in your post of the Cold War refers to Mutually Assured Destruction (MAD) quite the opposite of the above as neither party holds the advantage. And despite the fact that the US and USSR never pressed the button and ended it all, hundreds of thousands died in proxy wars across the globe. In fact one of the hotbeds for the Cold War was Afghanistan where Russia was fighting US supported rebels and we know what kind of mentality some of the children who grew up there now have. Just because tanks aren't driving down Main Street USA doesn't mean there's peace in the world.<br>
<br>
Examples of 'peace through warm fuzzy feelings of love and happiness', tricky one, but Germany and France havn't been to war for nearly 60 years, which is a record. South Africa only turned around once the sins of the past were acknowledged and people started to look forward. The revolutions of 1989 in Eastern Europe where tanks were stopped by people wielding flowers (and David Hasselhoff on the Berlin Wall). Northern Ireland (closer to home for me), the peace process is built on an end to fear (not a smooth road but getting there slowly). Plus a few recent peace deals in Africa after 20 or 30 years of war failed to resolve anything (and the US, your potential moral hegemon, failed to intervene, not suprising given the absence of natural resources).<br>
<br>
So should the US intervene against whoever out of Pakistan and India goes nuclear first? Should we expect Israel and the Palestinians to stop fighting because the US (the &quot;moral hegemon&quot;) will do what is morally right and smack both their behinds?<br>
<br>
I get the amoral, immoral thing, even without the capital M, I just think it's wrong. Why does an individual have a right to ignore basic morality just because they become President?<br>
<br>
I'm not intending to come off as a US basher here, far from it, I would much rather an active US than a return to isolationism. No reason the US should help anyone really.<br>
<br>
I just think its disingenuous to claim that the rest of the world benefits from the US following its own agenda. Bottom line, if you're Kuwait (or other oil providing country) and you get invaded expect help. If you attack the US or support those who do, expect to get bombed. If you're a small European, African, Asian or South American country at war or sponsoring terrorism in your neighbours lands carry on regardless.<br>
<br>
Fair play to you Edward for discussing all this without it getting personal or offensive. At the risk of boring the board *shouts of &quot;too late&quot; from the back*, I'll make this my last post on the thread.<br>
